Trevor Blackwell (tlb@chardonnay.harvard.edu) writes:

> Where does the random seed to PGP come from? (I assume this is an easy
> question - I just don't know the answer)

No, it is not an easy question. Actually, the easiest way to figure
out is to look at the source. In short, it main source of natural
randomness comes from measuring the time intervals between to
keystrokes entered by the user. Each time when the user types
something (usually - the pass phrase), those intervals are collected,
and their randomness it further improved by taking MD5 hash of it -
several times.

Regards,
Vesselin
